{"id":"1005.5101","submitter":"Sergey Petoukhov","authors":"Sergey V. Petoukhov","title":"Matrix genetics, part 5: genetic projection operators and direct sums","comments":"17 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.OT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The article is devoted to phenomena of symmetries and algebras in matrix\npresentations of the genetic code. The Kronecker family of the genetic matrices\nis investigated, which is based on the alphabetical matrix [C A; U G], where C,\nA, U, G are the letters of the genetic alphabet. The matrix P=[C A; U G] in the\nthird Kronecker power is the (8*8)-matrix, which contains 64 triplets.\nPeculiarities of the degeneracy of the genetic code are reflected in the\nsymmetrical black-and-white mosaic of this genetic (8*8)-matrix of 64 triplets.\nPhenomena of connections of this mosaic matrix (and many other genetic\nmatrices) with projection operators are revealed. Taking into account an\nimportant role of projection operators in quantum mechanics, theory of digital\ncodes, computer science, logic and in many other fields of applied mathematics,\nwe study algebraic properties and biological meanings of these phenomena. Using\nof notions and formalisms of theory of finite-dimensional vector spaces in\nbioinformatics and theoretical biology is proposed on the bases of the\ndescribed results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 May 2010 05:54:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-05-28"}
{"id":"1006.5406","submitter":"Enrico Prati","authors":"Enrico Prati, Matteo Belli, Simone Cocco, Guido Petretto, Marco\n  Fanciulli","title":"Adiabatic Charge Control in a Single Donor Atom Transistor","comments":"12 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.3551735","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We charge an individual donor with electrons stored in a quantum dot in its\nproximity. A Silicon quantum device containing a single Arsenic donor and an\nelectrostatic quantum dot in parallel is realized in a nanometric field effect\ntransistor. The different coupling capacitances of the donor and the quantum\ndot with the control and the back gates are exploited to generate a relative\nrigid shift of their energy spectrum as a function of the back gate voltage,\ncausing the crossing of the energy levels. We observe the sequential tunneling\nthrough the $D^{2-}$ and the $D^{3-}$ energy levels of the donor hybridized at\nthe oxide interface at 4.2 K. Their respective states form an honeycomb pattern\nwith the quantum dot states. It is therefore possible to control the exchange\ncoupling of an electron of the quantum dot with the electrons bound to the\ndonor, thus realizing a physical qubit for quantum information processing\napplications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 May 2010 09:27:56 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 Jun 2010 16:01:01 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 10 Aug 2010 16:03:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-05-19"}
